TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Ubiquity of the Technique of Goal Setting in Theories of and Approaches to Employee Motivation
AU  - Locke, Edwin A.
Y1  - 1978/07/01
PY  - 1978
DA  - 1978/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1978.4305786
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1978.4305786
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 594
EP  - 601
VL  - 3
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Goal setting is recognized, explicitly or implicitly, by virtually every major theory of work motivation. It was recognized explicitly by advocates of Scientific Management and of Management of Objectives. Ignored in early versions of Human Relations and expectancy (VIE) theory, it now is more openly acknowledged. Cognitive Growth and Organizational Behavior Modification deny the significance of goal setting in theory, but not when they are put into practice. The ubiquity of goal setting in these theories stems from the general recognition that rational human action is goal directed.
AB  - Goal setting is recognized, explicitly or implicitly, by virtually every major theory of work motivation. It was recognized explicitly by advocates of Scientific Management and of Management of Objectives. Ignored in early versions of Human Relations and expectancy (VIE) theory, it now is more openly acknowledged. Cognitive Growth and Organizational Behavior Modification deny the significance of goal setting in theory, but not when they are put into practice. The ubiquity of goal setting in these theories stems from the general recognition that rational human action is goal directed.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1978.4305786
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1978.4305786
